<HEADLINE>
FT  05 FEB 93 / Productivity in US increased 2.7% last year
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL PROWSE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
IT WILL not be long before people start talking of a US 'productivity
miracle'.
Figures published yesterday confirmed that output per hour in non-farm
businesses is growing at its fastest rate in two decades. Productivity rose
at an annual rate of 4 per cent in the fourth quarter of last year, and by
2.7 per cent in 1992 as whole. This represents a sharp turnaround after five
years in which productivity growth averaged about 0.5 per cent a year.
In recent congressional testimony, Mr Alan Greenspan, Federal Reserve
chairman, claimed the post-recession US economy was a 'different animal'. If
recent productivity gains were sustained, he said, the potential US
long-term growth rate might be substantially higher than the 2 to 2.5 per
cent assumed by most analysts.
The chairman said the reasons for faster productivity growth were not fully
understood but it probably reflected 'accelerating advances in computer
software and applications' that were making possible big gains in efficiency
in all sectors of the economy. Capital investment in computer technology has
soared in recent quarters.
The most encouraging aspect of yesterday's figures was the confirmation that
productivity is now rising rapidly in service-sector companies (everything
from banking and insurance to retailing and tourism), which account for
about three quarters of economic activity.
Manufacturing productivity grew at an annual rate of 3.8 per cent in the
fourth quarter, slightly slower than overall productivity, implying that
service industries, if anything, are improving their efficiency even more
rapidly than are manufacturers.
This is a new development. In the 1980s, US manufacturing productivity rose
rapidly as companies came to terms with tougher global competition. OECD
figures, for example, indicate that US manufacturing productivity grew by
about 55 per cent between 1980 and 1991, compared with gains of less than 40
per cent in Japan and Germany.
But inefficiency in the sprawling US service sector meant that overall
productivity growth was only about a third of the average pace of 1.5 per
cent a year in the industrialised world as a whole.
Better productivity figures augur well for inflation because the growth of
labour costs per unit of output is falling rapidly. Unit labour costs rose
at an annual rate of 0.6 per cent in the fourth quarter and by 0.7 per cent
relative to the equivalent period in 1991, the smallest annual rise since
the mid-1960s. If sustained, such low increases in unit labour costs could
result in a fall in inflation below the consensus forecast of 2.5 to 3 per
cent this year.
The surge in productivity growth explains a hitherto puzzling feature of the
current recovery: the juxtaposition of very bullish news on economic growth
(such as the 5.3 per gain in factory orders between November and December
reported yesterday) with depressing reports of big job cuts at leading
blue-chip companies such as IBM and Sears Roebuck.
For the first time since 1945, the US is experiencing a 'jobless recovery'.
Nearly all the growth of gross domestic product has reflected gains in
productivity, rather than increases in employment, which has barely moved
since the official end of the recession nearly two years ago.
Analysts are keenly awaiting the US employment figures for January, due
today, in the hope they will show the beginnings of a revival in
job-creation. But the chances are the US will have to learn to love
productivity-led growth.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  USA.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9611  Administration of General Economic Programs.
</IN>
