<HEADLINE>
FT  05 FEB 93 / What bakers say about Major: How a sector of small business
is surviving
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BETHAN HUTTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR John Major conjured with the image of a 'homely' local bakery to evoke a
benign image of his free-market philosophy when he made his Carlton Club
speech on Wednesday.
But how do bakers see the impact of the prime minister's policies?
Mr David Harbourne, director of the National Association of Master Bakers,
took Mr Major's comments as a pat on the back for his members' efforts to
improve their service.
'We do have the friendly face behind the counter which Mr Major touched on,
but we are not doing anywhere near as well as we might,' he says.
He pointed out that small bakers have been particularly badly hit by the
recession, as well as by Sunday opening by supermarket chains and uniform
business rate increases.
Mr Patrick Cross, owner of the Holborn Bakery in central London, has been
affected by high interest rates and says rent for his premises has doubled
in six years while nearby shops stand empty.
'We are in the middle of London and a lot of our customers are office
workers,' he explains. 'Many firms have moved out of this area in recent
years because of rent and rates and a lot of people have been made
redundant, so our customer base has dropped quite drastically.'
But for one baker in Bristol, Mr Major's 'workfare' proposal is the real
cause for alarm. His independent bakery in the Montpelier area has a high
proportion of residents claiming social security benefits. 'As long as they
keep on paying so many people for nothing, we will be all right.'
