<HEADLINE>
FT  05 FEB 93 / Exporters angry at cost of cover
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID DODWELL, World Trade Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THOUSANDS of British jobs are at risk and hundreds of millions of pounds in
exports are being lost because of the high cost and limited availability of
export credit cover, says a group of leading British exporters.
Recent examples include a Pounds 40m contract to build a urea complex in
China that will now be bid for by Snamprogetti in Italy instead of the
company's Basingstoke subsidiary. That is because an export credit insurance
premium of 2.1 per cent was offered by Italy's state insurer compared with
the 5.6 per cent premium required by Britain's Export Credits Guarantee
Department.
Exporters are inflamed by a letter from the ECGD this week telling them that
'as a result of recent business success in the (Indonesian) market, ECGD
cover is now fully committed and therefore we cannot currently accommodate'
cover for more business.
The letter arrived days after an intensive and strongly supported
export-promotion seminar on Indonesia in London by the Department of Trade
and Industry.
Evidence was presented this week to the Commons trade and industry committee
by a group of 10 leading UK companies active in construction, power plant
and engineering. They said the high cost of UK export finance presented
exporters with 'one of two unpalatable alternatives: to abandon the business
altogether, or to try to move as much work as possible offshore to countries
whose export credit authorities are more accommodating'.
</TEXT>
