<HEADLINE>
FT  05 FEB 93 / Police back cut in senior staff numbers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MANY POLICE officers favour abolishing some senior ranks to create a flatter
management structure, according to research commissioned for the
government's inquiry into police responsibility and rewards.
The research, by Ernst &amp; Young, management consultants, is one of the most
extensive examinations of the police conducted. Its findings make it
probable that when the inquiry reports in May, it will recommend a simpler
management structure and some form of performance-related pay.
Some provincial police forces have already delegated more responsibility to
local level, cutting down on chief superintendents. The Ernst &amp; Young survey
says the ranks of chief superintendent and chief inspector are the most
popular candidates among officers for abolition.
The survey says an important aspect of change in the police service over
recent years has been the 'injection of local innovation and experimentation
with different management systems'. This trend has the potential to
'increase the responsibilities and accountability of individual officers'.
Sir Patrick Sheehy, the chairman of BAT Industries who is chairing the
inquiry, said the study had identified opportunities to improve
accountability and operational effectiveness.
Lord Edmund-Davies, who conducted the last inquiry into police pay and
conditions in 1977-78, identified four factors that made police work unique
 -the independent status of the constable; risk of assault and injury;
prohibition of the right to strike; and disruption to family life. The new
report says there is no evidence that these have changed.
</TEXT>
