<HEADLINE>
FT  05 FEB 93 / Plants may be left out of Daf rescue
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT PESTON and KEVIN DONE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE DUTCH and Belgian operations of Daf, Western Europe's sixth-largest
truckmaker, may be demerged into a specially created company, financed by
local banks and the Dutch government.
The UK operations would not be transferred to the new company, senior
bankers said yesterday. Much of the UK's operations, which employ 5,500
people, could close.
Bankers said that the main truck plant at Leyland in Lancashire might be
sold to management, but the Birmingham van plant and Glasgow axle plant were
at risk.
They added that Daf's administrators - appointed on Tuesday under Dutch
insolvency law - are working on the demerger proposal with local bankers and
government officials.
Any demerger would need to be approved by the group's banks, principally a
consortium of nine led by the Dutch bank, ABN Amro. A formal proposal should
be submitted in the next three weeks.
New startling details also emerged yesterday about the extent of the
truckmaker's financial problems. A confidential report by accountants
Coopers &amp; Lybrand, prepared for Daf in the past few weeks, estimated that
the company's 1992 losses were in excess of Fl800m (Pounds 304m).
Coopers was studying the financial implications of a restructuring plan
based on work by both Daf and the consultants Arthur D. Little.
Under this plan, Daf would have abandoned van manufacturing and sought an
outside partner in light trucks. Vans are made at a Birmingham plant with
2,000 employees and light trucks are assembled at the Leyland plant, which
has 2,200 employees.
The biggest portion of last year's estimated loss stemmed from Coopers'
estimate that the company should make a charge of Fl580m to cover the costs
of restructuring its operations. Trading losses were more than Fl200m.
In order to carry out the reconstruction, Coopers estimated that Daf needed
to raise Fl800m of new finance in 1993. In 1994, a further Fl500m would have
been needed plus another Fl250m in 1995.
Under the rescue plan, this external finance would have come from three main
sources:
Daf's commercial banks.
The Dutch government and the Flemish regional authorities.
Holders of Daf's preference shares and debentures.
The scale of the new money required demonstrates why three UK banks and
Generale de Banque of Belgium refused on Monday to accede to a last-minute
demand from the Dutch and Flemish governments that the main providers of
finance should back the medium-term rescue plan.
These banks - whose UK members are National Westminster, Lloyds and Barclays
 -were prepared to put up funds only for the businesses' immediate
requirements. But they repeated their earlier demand that outside
accountants should verify Coopers' hastily prepared estimates of Daf's
future financing needs.
Not all the new money would have come in the form of new bank loans. Much of
it would have been conversions of debt into equity or injections from the
two governments.
Nevertheless, banks had already lent Fl900m to Daf's manufacturing
operations, plus a further Fl2bn to its finance companies.
They were therefore reluctant to give a commitment to put in hundreds of
millions more, until they knew how much was required.
Coopers said that if the restructuring was carried out, Daf would break even
in the current year. It also forecast a profit of Fl150m in 1994 and profits
of Fl200m in 1995.
The proposed restructuring was radical. In order to keep Daf's 1,300-strong
dealer network supplied with light commercial vehicles, the company had
planned to seek to purchase vans from another producer and then re-badge
them with the Daf name.
The Little study also concluded that Daf's position in the light truck
market was not strong enough to justify continuing to make these vehicles on
its own in Lancashire.
Daf would have searched for another partner in this business, such as MAN of
Germany or possibly Mercedes-Benz. Talks had been taking place with
Mercedes-Benz since last autumn about a possible exchange of components or
products.
However, the study concluded that Daf had a strong position in heavy and
medium size trucks and that an independent future manufacturing these was
possible.
It recommended that the company should buy a greater proportion of its
components and parts from outside manufacturers and should abandon its
integrated approach to manufacturing - it makes its own engines and axles.
Little said that in general the company needed to change the emphasis of the
business from volume manufacturing to profitability.
The restructuring proposals stemmed from a general analysis of Daf's
strengths and weaknesses. The weaknesses included the following:
Daf is the smallest of the full-line truck makers in Europe and the only
non-car maker with a van line.
It is too dependent on the UK, where margins on big trucks are the slimmest
in Europe and which has been hardest hit by the recession. Its presence in
Germany is far too small.
It tries to make too wide a range. As a result, the investment programme
required to keep it competitive is far too expensive, given its limited
financial resources.
Its interest burden, running at around Fl20m a year, is too high.
On the other hand, some strengths were listed:
It has the second newest range of truck models in Europe after Iveco (though
this advantage is about to disappear, as rivals introduce new models).
It is relatively good at serving customers, with an effective sales/service
network.
Though sales volumes have slumped, margins have held up relatively well.
Daf also confirmed yesterday that it had received a short-term bridging loan
from its banks and the Dutch government to allow it to continue trading for
a month. It has received a loan of more than Fl100m, including Fl60m from
the banking consortium.
Mr John Talbot, the administrative receiver for Leyland Daf in the UK, is
expected to meet the Dutch administrators for the first time today in the
Netherlands.
</TEXT>
<XX>
