FT  05 FEB 93 / Major refuses consideration of aid for Daf
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN MAJOR yesterday brushed aside calls for government financial aid to
Leyland Daf as 'simply not realistic' in spite of mounting pressure from
Labour to rescue the truck maker, Ivo Dawnay writes.
During angry exchanges in the Commons Mr Major refused to make any
commitment to match any intervention in the company from the Netherlands or
Belgium.
He told Mr John Smith, the Labour leader, that the receivers had made clear
that parts of the business could be saved without state funding. 'I believe
that is the way to proceed,' he said.
Mr Smith refused to accept the decision, arguing that it was 'vital' to
British manufacturing industry that the company should not be allowed to
collapse.
Earlier the cabinet had heard a report from Mr Michael Heseltine, the trade
and industry secretary, on the company.
