<HEADLINE>
FT  05 FEB 93 / Exporters angry at cost of cover
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID DODWELL, World Trade Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THOUSANDS of British jobs are at risk, and hundreds of millions of pounds in
exports is being lost, because of the high cost and limited availability of
export credit cover, says a group of leading British exporters.
Recent examples include a Pounds 40m contract to build a urea complex in
China that will now be bid for by Snamprogetti in Italy instead of the
company's Basingstoke subsidiary because an export credit insurance premium
of 2.1 per cent was offered by Italy's state insurer, compared with the 5.6
per cent premium required by Britain's Export Credits Guarantee Department.
Exporters are inflamed by a letter from the ECGD this week telling them that
'as a result of recent business success in the (Indonesian) market, ECGD
cover is now fully committed and therefore we cannot currently accommodate'
cover for more business.
The letter arrived days after an intensive and strongly supported
export-promotion seminar on Indonesia in London by the Department of Trade
and Industry.
Evidence was presented this week to the Commons trade and industry select
committee by major British Exporters, 10 leading UK companies active in
construction, power plant and engineering, that the high cost of UK export
finance presented exporters with 'one of two unpalatable alternatives: to
abandon the business altogether, or to try to move as much work as possible
offshore to countries whose export credit authorities are more
accommodating'.
Mr John Fletcher, Trafalgar House's marketing and business development
director, said ECGD refusal to provide cover for a Pounds 200m contract to
build a synthetic medicine plant in Russia forced his company to give the
work to its US subsidiary, where the US Eximbank was willing to offer cover.
The exporters' group called for ECGD country coverage comparable with that
of competitors; for premium rates to be harmonised with those of competitor
countries; and for the government to provide aid-supported finance where
competitors provided it.
</TEXT>
