<HEADLINE>
FT  05 FEB 93 / International Company News: Goldstrike mine boosts American
Barrick profit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
AMERICAN Barrick, defying the gloom in the gold-mining industry, announced a
near-doubling in 1992 earnings, an accelerated production schedule at its
flagship Goldstrike mine, and plans to broaden its horizons to Latin
America.
The Toronto-based company lifted net earnings to USDollars 174.9m, or
Dollars 1.22 a share, in 1992, from Dollars 92.4m, or 68 cents, the previous
year. Revenues from gold sales soared by 57 per cent to Dollars 540m.
The strong improvement was almost entirely due to higher production and
lower costs at the Goldstrike mine in Nevada. Goldstrike's output more than
doubled to 1.11m ounces last year.
Output from all five of the company's mines rose to 1.33m ounces from
790,000 ounces. Aggregate cash costs fell to Dollars 210 per ounce from
Dollars 305.
An active hedging programme held prices realised last year at an average
Dollars 422 per ounce, well above prevailing market levels. Mr Greg Wilkins,
chief financial officer, said yesterday output was fully hedged to the end
of 1994 at prices above Dollars 400, and the company was now hedging between
20 per cent and 25 per cent of its output up to 2001.
Thanks to a co-operation agreement signed late last year with Newmont
Mining, which owns deposits adjoining Goldstrike, Barrick forecasts its
total production will surpass 2m ounces by 1995, five years earlier than the
original target.
Barrick has also raised its estimate of ore reserves at Goldstrike's
Betze-Post pit by 20 per cent, bringing the company's total reserves to
27.2m ounces. The estimated grade at Betze-Post has been revised upwards to
0.22 ounces per ton from 0.19 ounces.
Exploration work at Goldstrike will continue this year. Mr Bob Smith,
Barrick's president, expressed confidence yesterday that 'the final chapter
on reserves at Goldstrike has yet to be written.'
Yesterday's announcements pushed Barrick's share price up 37 cents to
CDollars 38.75 on the Toronto Stock Exchange. The company, which had its
origins as a troubled oil and gas producer in the early 1980s, is ranked
eighth in market value on the TSE, ahead of such traditional giants of
Canadian business as Canadian Pacific and Alcan Aluminium.
</TEXT>
