<HEADLINE>
FT  05 FEB 93 / International Company News: Northwest Air deficit soars
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NORTHWEST Airlines, the fourth-largest US carrier in which KLM Royal Dutch
Airlines holds a significant minority stake, yesterday reported an after-tax
loss of Dollars 89.1m, before special charges, in the fourth quarter.
This compares with a Dollars 79.2m loss for the same period of 1991, and
brings the after-tax loss for the year to Dollars 156m - substantially
increased from the Dollars 3.1m deficit seen in 1991.
Including charges related to accounting changes, quarterly and annual losses
for the airline operations were Dollars 207.2m and Dollars 383m
respectively.
Meanwhile, NWA, the privately-owned parent company, incurred losses of
Dollars 139m (against Dollars 164.3m) and Dollars 405.1m (Dollars 316.9m) in
the fourth-quarter and 12-month periods respectively, with the charges
excluded.
With the addition of these items, the deficit widened to Dollars 682.4m in
the final three months of the year, and Dollars 1.06bn in 1992 overall.
Revenues were virtually unchanged at Dollars 1.93bn in the final quarter,
but increased by 5.3 per cent for the year overall to Dollars 8.13bn.
Northwest's figures complete the results season for the leading US airlines.
With the exception of Southwest Airlines, all carriers have shown heavy
fourth-quarter and annual losses before the accounting-related charges.
Mr John Dasburg, Northwest's chief executive, summed up the prevailing view
of the airline companies yesterday when he said the results 'underscore the
extremely difficult and predatory pricing environment in which this industry
operated beginning in April 1992'.
'The pricing environment and the slow economic recovery both domestically
and internationally made 1992 the third bleak year in a row for this
industry,' he noted.
</TEXT>
