<HEADLINE>
FT  05 FEB 93 / International Company News: Travelers faces Dollars 658m
loss as loan reserves increase
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
TRAVELERS, one the largest US composite insurers but beset by a troubled
property portfolio, yesterday said it would step up sales of foreclosed real
estate assets as the US property market recovers.
As a result of this, and the need to comply with a new fair value accounting
requirement, the company was bolstering property and mortgage loan reserves
by a further Dollars 735m, and warned it would post a Dollars 658m after-tax
loss for 1992.
Mr Edward Budd, Travelers chairman, claimed the strategy was designed to
'take early advantage of emerging liquidity developing in real estate
markets'. It would allow Hartford-based Travelers to redeploy investment
funds tied up in ailing property into assets offering a better return.
Over the past four-and-a-half years, the company has shed some Dollars 1.4bn
of foreclosed real estate assets. However, at end-1992, its mortgage loan
and real estate portfolio stood at Dollars 13.6bn (before valuation
reserves). Of this, Dollars 5.1bn-worth was classed as underperforming and
Dollars 2.3bn-worth as underperforming in the foreclosed category.
To reflect the disposal strategy and the accounting standard - which
requires the company to account for the foreclosed real estate held for sale
at fair value - Mr Budd said Travelers had written down almost all of its
foreclosed property assets and provided for disposal costs. It had increased
provisions for mortgage loans which might be affected by the new strategy.
As a result, the loss provision ratio, as related to the underperforming
property portfolio, stands at 38 per cent, and Travelers' total mortgage and
real estate reserves are about Dollars 1.5bn. At end-1991, the reserve for
potential property-related losses was Dollars 909m.
The increased provision will cause Travelers to post a net loss of Dollars
589m in the fourth quarter, and a Dollars 658m deficit - equivalent to
Dollars 6.51 a share - for the year. In 1991, the company reported after-tax
profits of Dollars 318m, or Dollars 2.97 a share.
</TEXT>
