<HEADLINE>
FT  04 FEB 93 / Parliament and Politics: Clash over council tax cuts fears
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR MICHAEL HOWARD, the environment secretary, last night sought to allay
fears that the council tax to be introduced in April would prove to be more
burdensome and unpopular than its predecessor, the community charge.
He told the Commons that the support provided by the Treasury should ensure
that the burden on local taxpayers could be held down to 'fair and
reasonable levels'.
Strongly disputing this view, Mr Jack Straw, Labour's chief spokesman on
local government, forecast that the financial constraints imposed on
councils would result in a serious decline in public services and thousands
of job losses.
Mr Howard insisted that overall, after allowing for inflation, there should
be no need for councils to raise more money in 1993-94 than in the current
year.
He stressed that, if necessary, the government would use its 'capping'
powers to restrain excessive spending and hold down council tax levels. Mr
Howard said Pounds 340m would be available to provide transitional relief
for individual householders facing an 'excessive increase' in the payments
they were required to make to local councils.
His assurances won over at least one waverer on the Tory backbenches. Sir
Rhodes Boyson (C Brent north), who would have preferred retention of the
poll tax, said that after 'wrestling with his conscience' he had decided to
vote for the government. Sir Rhodes called for an undertaking that the
transitional relief scheme would operate for more than one year.
Mr John Redwood, minister for local government, said the provision made by
the government for 1993-94 - approved by a majority of 57 (308-251)  - meant
there was no need for compulsory redunancies in any well-run authorities.
</TEXT>
