FT  04 FEB 93 / Parliament and Politics: Cabinet groups sidestep publicity
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN MAJOR met senior colleagues yesterday for his first full discussion
of the pit closures since his return from India and the Gulf.
The small group of ministers most involved, however, is not in Downing
Street's updated list of cabinet committees, since it is counted as an ad
hoc group rather than a formal committee.
The same is true for the group under Lord Wakeham, the leader of the Lords,
which has been set up to look specifically at unemployment and possible
employment measures.
Instead, the only two new committees listed are EDX, the public expenditure
committee, which is chaired by the chancellor, Mr Norman Lamont, and the
group on refugees from the former Yugoslavia, which is chaired by the home
secretary, Mr Kenneth Clarke.
EDX comprises Mr Lamont, Mr Clarke, Mr Michael Heseltine, the trade
secretary; Lord Wakeham, the leader of the Lords; Mr Tony Newton, the leader
of the Commons; Mr William Waldegrave, the public services minister; and Mr
Michael Portillo, the chief secretary.
The refugees group comprises Mr Clarke; Mr Douglas Hurd, the foreign
secretary; Mr Newton; Mr Michael Howard, the environment secretary; Mr David
Hunt, the Welsh secretary; Mr Peter Lilley, the social security secretary;
Mr Ian Lang, the Scottish secretary; Mr John Patten, the education
secretary; Mrs Virginia Bottomley, the health secretary; Mrs Gillian
Shephard, the employment secretary; Mr Portillo; Sir Nicholas Lyell, the
attorney general; Baroness Chalker, the overseas development minister; and
Mr Charles Wardle, a junior home office minister.
