FT  04 FEB 93 / Parliament and Politics: Calls for payment in BCCI collapse
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
OPPOSITION MPs yesterday renewed calls for a government commitment to
compensate customers who lost money when Bank of Credit and Commerce
International collapsed.
Mr Keith Vaz, Labour MP for Leicester East, used Scottish questions to
demand an assurance the government would accept the advice of a forthcoming
select committee report if it recommended compensation should be paid.
He was supported by Mr Charles Kennedy, Liberal Democrat MP for Ross
Cromarty &amp; Skye, who said he hoped the Scottish Office would take a more
'enlightened' view of the word compensation than the Treasury had in its
dealings with local councils.
But their appeals were sidestepped by Mr Allan Stewart, junior Scottish
minister, who said the government's response to the report would be a matter
for Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor.
The cross-party Treasury and Civil Service committee is expected to
recommend compensation for BCCI's former customers in a supplementary report
on the affair to be published later this month.
In a separate move, Mr Vaz stepped up his criticism of BCCI's liquidators
using a new parliamentary early day motion.
The motion expressed regret that Mr Christopher Morris - head of corporate
special services at Touche Ross and a joint BCCI liquidator - had 'failed to
justify his firm's astonishing and exorbitant fees'.
