<HEADLINE>
FT  04 FEB 93 / Parliament and Politics: Spring holds out olive branch to
unionists
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR DICK Spring, Ireland's foreign minister, yesterday said he wanted to meet
Northern Ireland's unionist leaders about demands for constitutional change
in the republic.
But he failed to dispel the belief that formal talks on the province will
not re-start for some time.
Speaking after an Anglo-Irish conference in London, Mr Spring appeared to
offer an olive branch to unionists who insist as a pre-condition for talks
that Ireland would, if necessary, amend its territorial claim to Ulster.
'I believe that constitutional change will be necessary,' Mr Spring said.
He stopped short of promising that changes would be put to an Irish
referendum if agreement was reached on political arrangements in the north.
'At this stage I don't think we want to get bogged down over 'could be' or
'would be'.' He said it was important for dialogue to open but his
invitations are unlikely to be accepted by the unionist leaders.
Mr Spring also emphasised setting out a lengthy programme of work for the
regular Anglo-Irish conferences, held under the 1985 Anglo-Irish Agreement
and opposed by unionists because of the role they give Dublin in the affairs
of the north.
That probably reflected an expectation in London and Dublin that talks will
not resume until after May's local elections in the province, which have
begun to provoke inter-party rivalries.
No proposals have been discussed for a break in the conference meetings  -
almost certainly needed if talks were to resume. But Sir Patrick Mayhew, the
Northern Ireland secretary, said the absence of a planned suspension would
not be an obstacle if there was a desire for talks to resume. He is likely
to meet nationalist and unionist leaders in the province shortly.
</TEXT>
