<HEADLINE>
FT  04 FEB 93 / Parliament and Politics: Warning on cuts to housing budget
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CUTS IN the government's housing budget threaten to reduce the quality of
homes for rent, force more tenants on to social security benefits and create
housing ghettos no better than the municipal housing estates of the 1960s, a
new campaign will claim today.
The Right to Build campaign will be launched by 15 housing associations at
today's annual meeting of association chief executives in Bristol. It is
likely to receive a warm reception from the executives, many of whom will
lose government funding for building new homes for rent if the cuts are
implemented.
In his Autumn Statement the chancellor reiterated the Conservative election
manifesto pledge of aid for 153,000 new housing association homes over the
next three years. But he announced that the housing association grant rate
would fall from about 72 per cent of the cost of each new home to 55 per
cent in 1995.
One consequence is that in 1995 housing associations will have to raise 45
per cent of the cost of each new home from the capital markets, rather than
28 per cent as now. This will make it much harder for associations to raise
the private capital they need. Tenanted property is normally valued at about
50 per cent of its cost so with a loan of 45 per cent it barely has adequate
security.
Mr Graham Buck of Samuel Montagu, the UK merchant bank, said: 'If
associations will be looking for more money I am not sure that there is the
institutional interest to lend more.'
Investors are likely to concentrate their funds on the most financially
sound housing associations. The Housing Corporation, which pays out
government housing grants, has anticipated this and prepared plans to reduce
the number of eligible associations from 600 to fewer than 90. The plan,
leaked shortly before Christmas, created uproar among housing associations.
Ms Sheila Button, chair of the Metropolitan Housing Association, said:
'Rationing funds to a few big housing associations seems to go against
everything the government has tried to do in breaking up big local authority
housing departments.'
Ms Leonie Cooper, chief executive of Rodinglea association, which
specialises in housing single people and students, said several of the
largest and most successful associations would be excluded from the new
'premier league'. She said: 'Special needs, co-operative and ethnic minority
associations are threatened, too.'
Builders fear that the reduced level of subsidy will mean lower quality
homes.
The higher level of private funding will also push up rents, to cover the
additional interest bill. Much of the extra rent will be covered by housing
benefit.
Mr Len Bishop, chief executive of Hyde housing association, one of the UK's
largest, said that as rents increase housing association developments will
become welfare ghettos with almost all tenants on benefit.
He said: 'The government will not save any money, because what it is taking
from housing associations with one hand it will have to pay back in
increased housing benefit.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
