<HEADLINE>
FT  04 FEB 93 / Braer disaster hits 2.5m salmon
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THE OIL from the wrecked Braer tanker contaminated 2.5m farmed salmon worth
Pounds 35m, the Shetland Salmon Farmers' Association said yesterday.
The fish were in pens in 16 fish farms in the exclusion zone the government
imposed off the west coast of Shetland after the Braer ran aground. The fish
will remain in the cages and will be monitored by scientists.
About half the affected salmon would have been ready for harvesting now, and
the rest would have been ready next year. The association stressed that the
remaining 75 per cent of Shetland fish farms were free of contamination and
unaffected by oil.
Scientists from the Scottish Office Agriculture and Fisheries Department
said all the salmon from inside the exclusion zone which were tested were
'tainted or badly tainted' with oil. But all the salmon from outside the
exclusion zone which were tested were uncontaminated.
</TEXT>
