<HEADLINE>
FT  04 FEB 93 / Caution on 'grey area' in tendering: Guidelines on
contracting out
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GOVERNMENT departments have been advised to take legal advice every time
work is put out to tender to determine whether the contract will be covered
by European Community laws protecting the jobs and conditions of employees
in mergers and acquisitions.
The Cabinet Office expects to issue guidance in the next few months on the
application to market-testing of the Transfer of Undertakings (Protection of
Employment) 1981 regulations.
The regulations implement the EC's 1977 acquired rights directive that
decisions in the European Court of Justice extend to contracting out of some
public services.
When the Tupe regulations apply the contractor must take over employees on
their existing terms and conditions. The 50-fold increase in the
government's market-testing programme has led to widespread confusion in
departments over when the regulations apply.
The Cabinet Office guidance will seek to clarify when the Tupe regulations
apply to contracting out. It is also co-ordinating the legal advice given to
departments through a group of departmental lawyers meeting under the aegis
of the Treasury solicitor.
Officials believe there remains a grey area in which it is difficult to
predict whether the regulations apply. The Cabinet Office therefore
recommends that legal advice be sought on each department's market-testing
programme case by case.
There are no plans to indemnify contractors who win contracts believing that
the regulations do not apply and subsequently find they do. Lawyers
specialising in employment law have recommended such indemnities to protect
contractors from uncertainties over the regulations' scope.
Britain's largest local authority, Strathclyde regional council, has decided
to specify that the Tupe regulations apply to all contracts compulsorily
tendered competitively.
The Department of National Heritage has signed an agreement with Sema Group
to provide all the information technology for the new department. The Pounds
3m a year contract is believed to be the first time a government department
has completely out-sourced its IT function.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Sema Group.
</CO>
<XX>
