<HEADLINE>
FT  04 FEB 93 / Ofgas to force delivery switch
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBORAH HARGREAVES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
OFGAS, the gas industry regulator, is taking legal steps to force British
Gas to transfer a Pounds 1.5bn gas supply contract to National Power's
station at Little Barford, Bedfordshire, instead of the Didcot site for
which it was earmarked.
National Power has put plans for two 680MW stations at Didcot, Oxfordshire,
on hold while uncertainty surrounds the market for gas-fired power because
of the government's energy review, National Grid said yesterday.
National Grid, which is owned by the 12 regional electricity companies, also
said that Southern Electric had shelved plans for a 351MW power station at
Fawley.
National Power asked British Gas last May to transfer its 500m-therm,
15-year gas contract from Didcot to Little Barford where construction of a
680MW station began last year and which should be operational in 1995.
However, since British Gas's supply contracts all specify a delivery site,
the company said it would need legal advice about changing the destination
of the gas.
Ofgas gave the go-ahead to change the site later last year, but British Gas
still demurred because of the political sensitivity surrounding gas-fired
power generation.
Mr Cedric Brown, British Gas chief executive, said the company was reluctant
to make any changes in its gas contracts at present.
'In the middle of the debate about the future of the coal industry, any
precipitate action would be tantamount to contempt of parliament,' he said.
After a formal complaint from National Power in December, Ofgas has started
legal proceedings against British Gas. The regulator should be in a position
to serve an enforcement order on the company by March. 'We've given them
every opportunity to arrive at a satisfactory conclusion but now we'll have
to force them,' said Ofgas.
</TEXT>
