<HEADLINE>
FT  04 FEB 93 / Receivers called in at Yugo importer
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GRIFFITHS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE UK importer of Serbian-built Yugo cars has gone into administrative
receivership, leaving 60,000 owners and the dealer network with fading hopes
of securing adequate supplies of replacement parts.
Zastava (GB)  - based at Reading in Berkshire  - which was controlled by the
Serbian export/import agent BSE Genex and traded as Yugo Cars, has seen its
supply of cars and replacement parts dry up since the UN imposed sanctions
on Serbia in May.
Only 2,000 cars were sold last year, compared with nearly 10,000 sales a
year in the late 1980s.
Just a handful of employees were left at the Reading headquarters when the
receiver was called in, compared with a peak of 125 during the height of
Yugo's sales success.
The receiver, Mr Keith Selley of Robson Taylor, the Bristol and Bath based
accountants, said yesterday he expected to complete a sale, possibly today,
of Zastava's assets  - mainly spare parts and a few vehicles.
Many of the Yugo dealers are trying to stay viable through second-hand car
sales and servicing, but the network has begun to break up, with some
switching to other makes.
The Yugo factory, at Kragujevac near Belgrade, has laid off most of its
workforce, with some reports indicating that it has switched part of the
facility to making armaments.
