FT  04 FEB 93 / Oil rig builders warn of 3,000 more job losses
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR and DEBORAH HARGREAVES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
OIL RIG fabricators warned yesterday that 3,000 jobs were expected to go in
the next three months as work in the UK section of the North Sea continues
to dry up.
The number of workers employed by offshore fabricators, including
sub-contractors, has halved to 10,000 since September, the Offshore
Manufacturers' and Constructors' Association (OMCA) said yesterday.
The association, along with representatives of North Sea oil and gas
operators, met Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary,
yesterday, to warn of the possible devastation if the government interfered
with gas-fired power station projects as part of its energy review.
'We expressed fears of an exodus of oil industry investment to other parts
of the world,' said Mr Harold Hughes, director-general of the UK Offshore
Operators Association, which has said 55,000 offshore and support jobs are
at risk if new gas projects do not go ahead.
A trade and industry select committee recently suggested that the government
look very carefully at approving further gas-fired power stations and
consider restricting gas-fired generators to supplying peak electricity
demand.
The OMCA warned job losses would be greater and that some construction yards
would face extinction if coal jobs were to be protected at the expense of
gas production.
Mr Bill Allison, its chief executive, said: 'In the long term 3,000
permanent jobs  - on top of the 3,000 expected to go in the next three
months  - could be lost by fabricators alone if the committee's
recommendations are accepted.'
Mr Arthur McQuillan, general manager of Amec Offshore, said the company's
Tyneside Yard had already halved its workforce to 2,000.
Mr Jim Franklin, managing director of McDermott Scotland, said it had
employed 3,500 at its peak last year but expected to reduce its labour force
to less than 100 by April.
