FT  04 FEB 93 / School testing prompts concern
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ASSESSMENT of pupils by teachers too often fails to tally with exam results,
the Schools Examinations and Assessment Council said in a report yesterday.
The report, based on teacher assessments of 14 year olds in maths and
science, will reinforce the government's determination to press ahead with
nationwide testing of pupils studying under the national curriculum in
England and Wales.
It comes amid growing controversy over the future of the curriculum in
English, and over this summer's English tests for 14 year olds.
Plans expected to be agreed today by the National Curriculum Council,
another government agency, will advocate a 'return to basics' in the
curriculum, with greater emphasis on spelling, grammar, punctuation and the
speaking of 'standard English'.
The teachers' unions think the English curriculum is too prescriptive and
are threatening industrial action if this year's tests for 14 year olds are
made compulsory, as intended.
A survey of English teachers in 145 grant-maintained schools by the
145,000-strong Association of Teachers and Lecturers found more than
two-thirds in favour of a boycott unless the government agreed not to
publish the results.
Mr Peter Smith, association general secretary, said: 'We are not opposed to
testing; we are opposed to the government's plan for compulsory testing this
year and the results being published in league tables.'
</TEXT>
