<HEADLINE>
FT  04 FEB 93 / Pound's fall puts up food prices
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GUY DE JONQUIERES, Consumer Industries Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
STERLING'S sharp fall in the past few days adds to the upward pressure on
food prices which has been developing since the pound left the European
exchange rate mechanism in the autumn. The full impact is likely to take
several months to show up in the shops.
Many leading manufacturers have announced higher prices in recent weeks.
McVitie's, part of United Biscuits, has raised its biscuit prices by 5 per
cent. Northern Foods, Marks &amp; Spencer's largest food supplier, aims for an
increase of between 6 per cent and 8 per cent by April.
Food manufacturers say the rises are needed to cover the higher costs of raw
materials which are imported or governed by Common Agricultural Policy
support schemes. The cost of some basic commodities, such as sugar and
flour, had risen by about 15 per cent before sterling's latest decline.
Many of the increases announced by manufacturers are facing stiff resistance
from leading supermarket chains, which face increasingly strong price
competition, particularly from the growing ranks of discount retailers.
Recession has caused many consumers to 'trade down' to cheaper brands and
pro-ducts.
When supermarkets agree to nominal increases in list prices they are said to
be whittling away much of the benefit to suppliers by insisting on bigger
volume discounts, more generous price promotions and special offers.
Some big retail chains are also said to have been accepting price rises for
branded products, but refusing to pay more for competing 'private label'
items  - often supplied by the same manufacturer  - which they sell under
their own name.
</TEXT>
