<HEADLINE>
FT  04 FEB 93 / The DAF Crisis: Arthur Andersen partners appointed as
receivers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN Talbot and Mr Murdoch McKillop, partners in Arthur Andersen, the
sixth-largest accountancy firm, were yesterday appointed as receivers to
Leyland-Daf's principal UK subsidiaries.
They have three months under UK insolvency law to hold a creditors' meeting.
During that time they may be able to hold a number of the trading companies
together and sell them as operating businesses.
The receivership is not affected by the jurisdiction of the courts in the
Netherlands, where the Leyland-Daf holding company is based, or by those in
Belgium. The management is applying for protection from creditors in both
countries.
In practice, the receivers are likely to work closely with their
counterparts in these countries.
The appointment of the British receivers prevents any creditor being able to
launch separate legal proceedings to seize the company's assets and recover
outstanding debts.
They have assigned a number of other accountants and insolvency specialists
from the firm to take control of the management of three UK operating
companies on six sites.
Unless they are granted an extension, the receivers will be expected to
provide a statement on the financial state of affairs at a creditors'
meeting by early May.
A creditors' committee would normally be elected at that time, and any
future negotiations - including monitoring the professional fees charged -
would be channelled through this committee.
In the meantime, they can expect a series of potential buyers for the Daf
businesses to come forward.
</TEXT>
