FT  04 FEB 93 / Charter on rights rejected by ANC
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JOHANNESBURG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE African National Congress (ANC) yesterday rejected the South African
government's draft human rights charter, saying it was a prescription to
maintain white privilege, Reuter reports from Johannesburg.
'The charter fails to outlaw discrimination and racism. The equality
provision is extremely weak. The charter condones the disenfranchisement of
the majority,' the ANC said in a statement.
Justice Minister Kobie Coetsee published a draft human rights charter on
Tuesday that outlaws discrimination, but provides for capital punishment and
detention without trial.
The rejection came as angry taxi drivers yesterday continued their protests.
They stoned buses and attacked bus drivers in Soweto, the biggest black
township. Police tried to stop the protest spreading to central
Johannesburg.
Two people have been killed and dozens injured in running battles between
police and the protesting taxi drivers. The drivers allege they are
constantly harassed by police and seek government subsidies.
