<HEADLINE>
FT  04 FEB 93 / World Trade News: IMF puts its terms for Dollars 3bn loan to
Moscow
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LEYLA BOULTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
TALKS on a standby programme which could unlock an extra Dollars 3bn (Pounds
1.9bn) International Monetary Fund loan could start when Russia confirms it
will act decisively on macroeconomic stabilisation and structural reform, Mr
Michel Camdessus, IMF managing director, told Izvestiya yesterday.
The world would 'not understand' if Moscow agreed an ambitious programme but
did not implement it. Western financial support would only be forthcoming if
Russia acted to strengthen monetary and financial policy.
It would have to ensure 'the money stays in Russia and does not immediately
end up in bank accounts in Zurich, Paris or London'. Moscow should stop
hyperinflation 'at any price'; many democrats had been 'killed' by it. Any
programme would have to suit not just the Fund, but be accepted by Russian
society. The west had delivered all the Dollars 24bn package promised to
Russia last year except for a Dollars 6bn rouble stabilisation fund.
Russia had received debt relief worth Dollars 7.2bn, plus Dollars 12.6bn
fresh credit from other countries, the EC, the European Bank for
Reconstruction and Development, and finally a first Dollars 1bn from the
Fund.
Russian exports fell 25 per cent last year to Dollars 38.1bn in sales
outside the former Soviet Union, the official Goskomstat statistics agency
reported.
</TEXT>
