<HEADLINE>
FT  04 FEB 93 / Major hints at work-related unemployment benefits
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN MAJOR last night held out the prospect of workfare-style schemes for
the unemployed and hinted at a review of the benefits system as part of a
re-examination of spending priorities.
In a wide-ranging speech on his personal vision of Conservatism, the prime
minister also warned of government action on road pricing and police reform.
Mr Major said he was questioning whether paying unemployment benefit
'without offering or requiring any activity in return' served either society
or the jobless well.
Referring to the Restart training programme that removes benefits from
non-attenders, he said: 'I believe we should explore ways of extending it
further.'
Mr Greville Janner, Labour chairman of the cross-party employment select
committee, last night wrote to Mr Major asking if he was merely 'kite
flying' ideas for a workfare-style programme and, if not, to give evidence
to the committee on his proposals.
Labour signalled its opposition to such a programme. Mr Donald Dewar, social
security spokesman, said the unemployed should be given the incentive and
opportunity to earn their keep, not punished for the misfortune of being
unemployed.
Mr Major promised a re-examination of long-term expenditure trends, and
reaffirmed the goals of sound public finance, lower personal taxation, firm
control of inflation and 'a rigorous approach to public expenditure'.
In a reference interpreted as signalling a fresh look at benefits, he added:
'It is always dangerously easy for the state to settle into habits of
spending which outlast their purpose and outrun their budgets.'
He said it was the Conservatives' task in the 1990s to break down class
barriers, raise the status of vocational qualifications and expand choice in
schools.
He also argued for respect for individual achievement and the gradual
evolution of traditional political institutions from the monarchy and
parliament to churches and voluntary organisations. As an example of this
need for evolutionary change, the honours system should be reformed to
stress merit. 'It is time to get rid of old, class-based distinctions,' he
said.
His words suggested that he plans to pre-empt the Labour party, which is
engaged in a fundamental re-evaluation of its policies on tax and benefits,
including those for the unemployed.
Other policy developments signalled in the speech included reforms to
teacher training, custodial sentences for persistent young offenders,
further deregulation and government help for business by means of opening
doors to markets.
A party aide said the latter aim was to bolster trade initiatives through
government-to-government contacts such as last week's prime ministerial tour
in India and the Gulf.
His speech, at the Carlton Club in London, was firmly placed in the context
of updating party thinking to address issues of the 1990s. It attempted to
yoke Disraeli's concept of 'one nation' Toryism with warnings of the dangers
of big government to support Mr Major's goal of building a classless society
of responsible individuals and 'a nation at ease with itself'.
Mr Major said the paradox Conservative politicians had to face was that
change was essential to preserve the best aspects of society. He stressed
that the era of deference was 'out of date, damaging and divisive'.
Agenda of change, Page 9
</TEXT>
