<HEADLINE>
FT  04 FEB 93 / International Capital Markets: Chinese stock exchanges
consider computer links
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By AP-DJ
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   HONG KONG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Shanghai Stock Exchange may attempt to unify with the Shenzhen Stock
Exchange, AP-DJ reports from Hong Kong.
China's official Xinhua news agency quoted the Shanghai exchange president,
Mr Wei Wenyuan, as saying he would 'enhance links' with the Shenzhen stock
market. He suggested that a joint computer system would expand the business
of both markets and erase some problems for investors.
Currently, the Shanghai and Shenzhen markets operate independently and under
different rules. Shanghai operators have previously indicated an interest in
bridging co-operation with Shanghai.
Shanghai's transaction volume hit a record Yn23.95bn (Dollars 3.99bn) in
January and was 18 times above January 1991's level. Last year, turnover in
Shanghai was Yn64.8bn, seven times higher than the year earlier.
The first initial public offer this year of a company on the Shenzhen bourse
has been planned for listing this month.
The simultaneous launch for both the domestic and foreign markets of Chiwan
Harbour shares will be internationally lead-managed by Standard Chartered
Asia and domestically by China Merchant Bank Securities.
The issue will raise a total of between Yn200m and Yn250m.
Standard Chartered and China Development Finance will underwrite the offer.
