<HEADLINE>
FT  04 FEB 93 / Fokker shares fall 24% after request for Fl 1bn loan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WALLER and DAVID BROWN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT, AMSTERDAM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SHARES in Fokker, the hard-pressed Dutch aircraft manufacturer, lost a
quarter of their value on the Amsterdam bourse yesterday after the company
said it had approached the Nationale Investeringsbank (NIB), the Dutch
state-owned bank, for a loan of between Fl 800m and Fl 1bn (Pounds 377m).
The move intensified fears that Deutsche Aerospace (Dasa), the aerospace
subsidiary of Germany's Daimler-Benz group, was considering abandoning its
plan to acquire a controlling stake in the Dutch company. It was also taken
as a sign of mounting financial difficulties at Fokker.
Fokker shares closed 24.4 per cent lower yesterday at Fl 10.20. The shares
were also dragged down by concern over the collapse this week of Daf, the
Dutch truckmaker.
Although Dasa said yesterday it was still interested in taking control of
Fokker, the German company is understood to be demanding a restructuring of
the provisional agreement signed at the end of October, saying the Dutch
group's financial and business position has deteriorated since then.
Dasa agreed to pay DM800m (Pounds 340m) for a 51 per cent stake in the Dutch
manufacturer of regional and commuter aircraft as part of its strategy to
create a European regional aircraft consortium. But the German group is
understood to believe that the capital injection from the Dutch authorities
agreed under the original proposal is now insufficient.
Dasa is anxious to avoid repeating with Fokker the embarrassment of having
to refinance a company shortly after completing its acquisition as happened
after it bought Dornier, the German aircraft maker.
However, it is willing to increase its own capital commitment to the company
if the Dutch government increases its cash support. The total capital
required is believed to be in the region of Fl 400m.
The Dutch government has indicated its willingness in principle to a change
in the agreement, but Dasa's requirements may prove too onerous. Dasa is
believed to be threatening to walk away from the deal if the transaction is
not restructured.
Dasa did not have access to all Fokker's accounts when it signed the
original agreement. It is believed to have been particularly concerned about
Fokker's backlog of unsold aircraft and has become worried about
deterioration in the aircraft market.
Dasa believes that Fokker's decision to seek the financing from the NIB
confirms its own assessment of mounting financial difficulties. Fokker said
yesterday that the request for a new loan would have been made irrespective
of the outcome of negotiations with Dasa.
</TEXT>
