<PROFILE>_AN-DBDCDAAIFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930204
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  04 FEB 93 / Rate falls prompt novel debt instrument
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONIA SHARPE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DEMAND from investors looking to preserve their income following recent
falls in UK base rates yesterday prompted the first public issue of
sterling-denominated instruments which pay a higher return as interest rates
fall.
This follows last week's launch of a wave of novel debt instruments by UK
building societies which were also aimed at satisfying demand for
higher-yielding sterling paper.
Yesterday, Abbey National, the Halifax Building Society and Eksportfinans,
the Norwegian government's import-export agency, each issued Pounds 100m
worth of so-called 'reverse' floating-rate notes. The yield on these notes,
for which there is a minimum investment of Pounds 100,000, increases each
time interest rates fall.
The notes offer the holder a fixed return of 7 per cent for the first six
months. For the rest of the notes' three-year life, the coupon will be fixed
at 12 3/8 per cent minus six-month Libor (London Inter Bank Offered Rate),
which stood at 5 7/8 per cent yesterday.
An official at UBS Phillips &amp; Drew, which arranged the deal for the Halifax,
said there was good demand for the issue from domestic and continental
institutions, especially income and money-market funds which were having
difficulty in finding high-yielding sterling investments.
Last week, the Leeds Permanent Building Society launched the first
sterling-denominated 'collared' floating-rate notes, followed closely by
Bradford &amp; Bingley and Halifax. These issues, each of Pounds 100m, offered
investors a minimum interest rate (floor) and a maximum interest rate (cap).
Under this structure, the holder receives a higher return than current money
market rates, but will not benefit if rates rise above the level of the cap.
The warm reception to yesterday's reverse floating rate notes reflected a
growing feeling among investors that UK rates are set to fall further, in
spite of government denials of media reports that further cuts are already
planned.
The issuers are believed to have taken steps to protect themselves against
paying out more to the note holders in the event of a base rate cut through
a series of transactions in the swap market, which has left them with
floating rate liability.
Lex, Page 20; Details, Page 29
</TEXT>
