<HEADLINE>
FT  04 FEB 93 / Rifkind reprieves 3,000 jobs in army about-face
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WHITE, Defence Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT yesterday sought to head off growing pressure to reverse army
cuts by announcing the reprieve of 3,000 uniformed jobs and the cancellation
of two regimental mergers.
The army, now about 145,000-strong, will be reduced to 119,000 instead of
the controversial 116,000 target set by the government in 1991.
But Mr Malcolm Rifkind, defence secretary, said in a Commons statement that
the size of the armed forces should not be permanently fixed. He promised to
keep army strength 'under close review in the light of changing
circumstances'.
The surprise change of mind by the government appeared calculated to take
the wind out of the sails of the Commons defence committee, which is to
publish a highly critical report next week calling for the army cuts to be
frozen while requirements are reconsidered.
Officials, however, said adjustments to the 1991 plans had been under
consideration for some months. The Ministry of Defence will have to find
savings of Pounds 80m in other areas of its budget to meet the annual cost
of the change in manpower plans.
Sir Nicholas Bonsor, the defence committee's Conservative chairman, welcomed
the changes, although next week's report would call for 'substantially
more'. He said the government should be prepared to raise numbers further if
UN requirements increased.
Mr David Clark, Labour's def-ence spokesman, described the changes as 'panic
measures' and said they reflected the lack of a national strategy for
defence.
The announcement that four infantry regiments would be saved from
amalgamating into two were greeted with loud cheers from MPs. The Cheshire
Regiment, now in central Bosnia, was due to merge with the Staffordshire
Regiment in September, and the Royal Scots, the oldest 'line' regiment in
the army, was set to join with the King's Own Scottish Borderers in October
next year.
The army will be left with 40 infantry battalions instead of the 38
previously planned. Until recently there were 55. The reprieve will also
allow other units to be brought up to strength.
Mr Rifkind said the streamlining of support services and the hiving off of
some activities should release a further 2,000 personnel for front-line
units.
Reorganisation has meant the gap between emergency tours of duty in Northern
Ireland or overseas is down to about 15 months. Mr Rifkind said the measures
would increase the interval to 17 months this year, and eventually it would
be more than the previous target of 24 months.
</TEXT>
