<HEADLINE>
FT  03 FEB 93 / BP arm in energy deal with Ford
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBORAH HARGREAVES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BP ENERGY, a subsidiary of British Petroleum, has won a contract to manage
the energy requirements of Ford's Halewood plant on Merseyside - the largest
ever UK contract energy project.
The move could save the plant more than Pounds 1m a year on its Pounds 11m
fuel bill for 210MW of energy - equivalent to the heating requirements of a
small town.
As well as obtaining the cheapest deal, BP Energy will make any changes in
the plant's energy systems, such as the construction of a combined heat and
power plant, if they provide cost savings.
BP Energy's responsibilities at Halewood include steam production for making
gear boxes, high-pressure hot water for air conditioning, compressed air for
manufacturing, electricity and water distribution systems and all heating
and ventilating at the plant.
Mr Nick Coleman, managing director of BP Energy, said: 'Out-sourcing energy
operations is now an option which more major industrial companies are
seriously considering.'
The contract energy management business is in its infancy but with most UK
utilities now privatised more companies are turning to specialist managers.
BP Energy is targeting all industrial, commercial and public-sector sites
with energy demand greater than 2MW - a market where energy costs exceed
Pounds 9bn.
</TEXT>
