<HEADLINE>
FT  03 FEB 93 / Parliament and Politics: Government tries to reassure
passengers
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government yesterday attempted to reassure passengers that the so-called
network benefits of a single national railway would not be lost as a result
of fragmentation by franchising.
The national timetable would be preserved, it said. So would
through-ticketing, making it possible to book tickets from principal
stations in one franchise area to stations in other franchise areas.
However, this would not be possible for all journeys, such as those
commencing at unmanned stations.
Railcards giving discounts to disabled people would be continued as a
special concession.
The Department of Transport offered no guarantees on the continuation of
other benefits such as bargain fares. But Mr John MacGregor, transport
secretary, said it would be in the commercial interests of private sector
train operators to get more passengers on to the railways by offering
attractive fares.
</TEXT>
