<HEADLINE>
FT  03 FEB 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICIA MORISION
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Enoch Powell (C4, 9.45) is a repeat of a programme in which the eloquent old
statesman returns to Cambridge and reminisces about his life in the
university in the thirties and the profound and lifelong impact upon him of
A. E. Housman's lectures on textual criticism and classical literature.
The impact of the arrival of television on the workings of the fame machine
is explored in the fifth episode of Clive James - Fame in the Twentieth
Century (BBC 1, 9.30), although 'explored' is too serious a word for this
frivolous and banal series. It is mildly watchable in the same way as
rifling through old magazines but with the benefit (or otherwise) of
listening to James's inimitable one-liners. This week the line-up includes
Lucille Ball, Liberace, and Grace Kelly, and tyro politicians learning to
come to terms with the new medium.
Eastern Europeans have a passion for mushrooms, hence the title of the new
comedy drama serial dealing in East-West relations, The Mushroom Picker
which starts tonight (BBC 2, 9.25), starring Nigel Terry who played the
starring role in Derek Jarman's Caravaggio.
</TEXT>
